'''Dizelaši''' (singular '''dizelaš''') was an [[urban culture|urban]] street [[youth culture|youth]] sub-culture popular in the 1990s in [[Serbia]]. It has been described as a mainstream fashion and social subculture,{{sfn|NOIZZ 2017}} that of a [[working class]], similar to the British ''[[Chav]]'', French ''racaille'' and Russian ''[[Gopnik]]''.{{sfn|Vice 2016}} The French movie ''[[La Haine]]'' (1995) is often mentioned in relation to these subcultures.<ref>{{harvnb|Vice 2016}}, {{harvnb|Highsnobiety 2017}}</ref> It was characterized by [[turbo-folk]],{{sfn|NOIZZ 2017}} [[hip-hop]] and [[dance music|dance]] music (such as [[Đogani]]),{{sfn|NOIZZ 2017}} [[designer clothes]] (such as [[Diesel (brand)|Diesel]]), embroidered sweatshirts{{sfn|NOIZZ 2017}} and [[Sportswear (activewear)|sportswear]]{{sfn|Vice 2016}} (such as [[Nike Air Max]]<ref>{{harvnb|Vice 2016}}, {{harvnb|NOIZZ 2017}}, {{cite web|title=On To It Subcultures That Rep Nike Air Max|publisher=Oyster|url=http://new.oystermag.com/on-to-it-subcultures-that-rep-nike-air-max}}</ref> and [[Reebok Pump]]{{sfn|Vice 2016}} shoes and [[Kappa (company)|Kappa]]{{sfn|Vice 2016}} sweatsuits) and link [[Jewellery chain|chains]].{{sfn|NOIZZ 2017}} Track jackets were tucked into the bottom pants which in turn were tucked into socks, as to conceal goods; it is said that legendary gangster [[Aleksandar Knežević Knele|Knele]] (1971–1992) popularised it, having used it as a tactic ensuring his gun would slide into his socks rather on the pavement when running from the police.{{sfn|Vice 2016}}

It emerged in [[Belgrade]] in the late 1980s and became popular by 1992,{{sfn|Vice 2016}} in a [[Sanctions against Yugoslavia|period of embargo]] on [[FR Yugoslavia]] following the outbreak of the [[Yugoslav Wars]]. The youths were stereotyped as gangsters (also called ''mangupi''), involved in illegal activities{{sfn|NOIZZ 2017}} such as fuel smuggling. The Russian counterpart is the [[Gopnik]] sub-culture, with which it is grouped together into "Post-Soviet fashion" that has become popular in recent years.{{sfn|Highsnobiety 2017}}<ref>{{cite news|title=KAD TE INSPIRIŠU RUSKI "DIZELAŠI" Želeli su da ih ismeju, ali stvorili nešto MNOGO VEĆE (VIDEO)|publisher=Blic|url=https://www.blic.rs/vesti/svet/kad-te-inspirisu-ruski-dizelasi-zeleli-su-da-ih-ismeju-ali-stvorili-nesto-mnogo-vece/9bgern2}}</ref> In contrast to the ''dizelaši'', the opposing sub-culture was called ''padavičari'', including [[hippies]], [[rocker (subculture)|rockers]], [[Heavy metal subculture|metalheads]] and [[rave]]rs.  A typical dizelaš was seen as:

{{cquote|A youngster, short-cut [hair], in a [[track suit]], with a gold chain around his neck, a mobile phone (possibly a good car), often tied to criminal activities.<ref name="Милорадовић2012">{{cite book|author=Софија Милорадовић|title=Музички жаргон младих и молодежный музыкальный сленг : компаративни поглед|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=8BrQvY8pLxoC&pg=PA80|year=2012|publisher=Etnografski institut SANU|isbn=978-86-7587-066-1|pages=80–|quote=младић кратко подшишан, у тренерци, са златним ланцем око врата, има мобилни телефон (евентуално и добар ауто), често повезан са криминалним радњама“ }}</ref>}}

The resurge of the fashion has been dubbed ''Neodizelaši''.{{sfn|Popboks}} The 1995 documentary about Belgrade gangsters, ''[[Crime that Changed Serbia]]'', is an icon of the culture.
