{{Infobox scholar | name = Miriam Cooke | image = Miriam_Cooke.jpg | imagesize = | alt = | caption = | fullname = | othernames = | birth_name = <!-- Use only if different from full/othernames --> | birth_date = | birth_place = | death_date = | death_place = | death_cause = | residence = | era = | region = | workplaces = [[Duke University]] | alma_mater = [[St Antony's College, Oxford]] | thesis_title = | thesis_url = | thesis_year = | doctoral_advisor = | doctoral_students = | notable_students = | school_tradition = | main_interests = Middle Eastern and Arab world studies | principal_ideas = | major_works = | awards = | influences = | influenced = | website = | footnotes = }} '''Miriam Cooke''' is an American academic in Middle Eastern and Arab world studies. She focuses on modern Arabic literature and critical reassessment of women's roles in the public sphere. She was educated in the United Kingdom,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.charlierose.com/guest/view/7187 |title=Guests: Miriam Cooke |work=Charlie Rose Show online |accessdate=14 May 2013 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131207125454/http://www.charlierose.com/guest/view/7187 |archivedate=7 December 2013 |df= }}</ref> and is co-editor of the ''[[Journal of Middle East Women's Studies]]''.<ref name=About>{{cite web |title=Journal of Middle East Women's Studies: About the journal | url= http://jmews.org/about/the-journal/ |publisher= [[Duke University Press]] |accessdate= 30 August 2015 }}</ref>
She is a professor of modern [[Arabic literature]] and culture at [[Duke University]]. She received her doctorate from the [[St Antony's College, Oxford]] in 1980.
