The '''Royal Corps of Halberdiers''' is a fictional British regiment from [[Evelyn Waugh]]'s  ''[[Sword of Honour]]'' trilogy. In the novel, the regiment is described as being composed of four [[battalions]]: The 1st (Regular [[Infantry]]) 2nd ([[Territorial Army (United Kingdom)|Territorial Army]]), 3rd ([[Commando]]s), and 4th ([[Militia]]). The Corps is derived from Waugh's own experiences in the [[Royal Marines]] throughout [[World War II]]. 

The Halberdiers are commanded by an officer called a 'Captain-Commandant' &mdash; a rank derived from the Corps's purported origins as the [[Robert Devereux, 2nd Earl of Essex|"Earl Of Essex's Honourable Company Of Free Halberdiers"]] during the reign of [[Elizabeth I]] (the [[halberd]] being a popular [[heavy infantry]] weapon of the time). The rank is analogous with [[Colonel]].<ref name="P31">''Sword of Honour'', Chapter 1</ref>

The [[Colonel-in-Chief]] of the Regiment since 1902 was the Grand-Duchess Elena of Russia.  The nicknames of the Regiment were the "Applejacks", after an account of the Corps in an orchard during the Napoleonic Wars repelling a French attack by hurling apples at them, and the "Copper Heels". 

